{
  "texts": [
    "Heterogeneous T cell states were defined by combinatorial expression of genes reflecting responses to various microenvironmental stimuli while being tightly associated with T cell receptor (TCR) utilization 35.",
    "These data thus suggested that TCR specificities may contribute to the spatial organization of T cells through the disposition of cognate antigens, facilitating their exposure to niches differing in the extent of inflammation, hypoxia, expression of activating ligands and inhibitory receptors, and nutrient supply.",
    "To investigate this hypothesis, we performed ST profiling of eight primary tumors from an ER + patient, a patient with classic TNBC and two patients with metaplastic TNBC breast cancer (MBC) (two biological replicates each) (Supplementary Table 1 and Methods).",
    "The resulting data, alongside published datasets 18 from a total of six ER + patients and patients with TNBC breast cancer (one biological replicate per patient), were analyzed using Starfysh.",
    "We first dissected the spatial heterogeneity in an individual TNBC tumor and characterized 29 diverse cell states, including normal epithelial, cancer epithelial, immune cells (naive CD4 + T cells, effector memory CD4 + T cells, myeloid-derived suppressor cells (MDSCs), macrophages, CD8 + T cells) and stromal cells (endothelial, perivascular like (PVL), immature PVL)."
  ]
}